Standard response.

Black tries a little reverse Kings Gambit action.
White protects King Pawn.
Black Queen comes out in aggressive style.
White blocks the check.
Blank Queen is forced to retreat.
White continues to push pawns.  Notice the white king is becoming naked and rather exposed to the elements.
Black continues in his aggressive ways.  This is the second check of the white king and its very early in the game.
White blocks the check in a very acceptable way.

Rather than swapping Bishops, black decides to just maintain the pressure and protect the Bishop.  Notice that if white decides to swap Bishops then the Black pawn structure will be a little messed up.  Black takes this chance as an acceptable risk.  If it does happen, the Black Rook opens up his file which is not a bad thing.
White decides to shoe away the black Bishop.

Black bishop is forced to retreat.  Notice that white keeps moving pawns and the white pieces are more and more exposed.  The King and Queen are becoming embarrassed as if the shades are open in the bathroom.
White Pawns continue to march forward.  Black is thinking, my opponent is some kind of "wood pusher."
Black develops normally.
White Bishop comes out from under cover and makes a threat upon a pawn.
Black pawn says the heck with you and instigates a swap.
White swaps pawns as expected.
Black opens a path so that we now have Bishop against Bishop.  Some may say this is a bad idea for black because a bishop swap will eliminate any chance for a queen side castling.
